    "content": "# Bug Investigation: Go CLI process crash during agent delegation\n\nRush runs AI agents via a Go CLI (`example/cli`) using the `harness` SDK. The CLI streams events to an Electron app via stdout NDJSON. Events are emitted via a hook system вЂ” hooks can be sync or async (run in goroutines).\n\n## What happened\n\nDuring a multi-agent research session, the CLI process crashed with a Go runtime panic when delegating to a child agent. The process died instantly вЂ” no graceful error, no logs persisted. The notification showed a raw Go stack trace.\n\n## Files to read\n\n1. **`harness/agent/hooks.go`** вЂ” Read the ENTIRE file. Focus on `emitEventImmediate()` and `emitEventWithWait()`. Both spawn goroutines for async hooks using `go func()`. Check: do these goroutines have `defer recover()`?\n\n2. **`harness/agent/agent.go`** вЂ” Read lines 399-560. The `Execute` method has `defer func() { if r := recover(); r != nil { ... } }()` at line 527. In Go, `recover()` only catches panics in the SAME goroutine. Does this protect against panics in hook goroutines?\n\n3. **`harness/agent/delegate_agent.go`** вЂ” Read lines 740-755. The async delegation path has `defer func() { if r := recover(); r != nil { ... } }()` inside its goroutine. Compare this with the hook goroutines in hooks.go.\n\n## Your task\n\nIdentify the root cause: why can a panic in the hook system crash the entire Go process despite `Execute` having `recover()`? What is the fix?\n\n\nWhen you're done, provide a brief summary of:\n1. What you did (1-2 sentences)\n2. Key files modified and why\n3. Any important classes, functions, or components you added/changed"
  },
